text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">The<span>&nbsp;</span><strong style="box-sizing: border-box;">math role</strong><span>&nbsp;</span>can be used for inline mathematical expressions:<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; white-space: nowrap;" class="pre">:math:`\psi(r)</span> = <span style="box-sizing: border-box; white-space: nowrap;" class="pre">\exp(-2r)`</span></span><span>&nbsp;</span>will produce<span>&nbsp;</span><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>ψ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>exp</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math>. Inside the backtics you can write anything you would write between dollar signs in a LaTeX document.<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box;" class="fn-bracket">[</span>1<span style="box-sizing: border-box;" class="fn-bracket">]</span></p><aside style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block; margin: 1em 16px; border: thin solid silver; padding: 0.5em 1em; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;" class="admonition tip"><p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0.5em; font-weight: bold;" class="admonition-title">Tip</p><p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0px;">If you put<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal">.. <span style="box-sizing: border-box; white-space: nowrap;" class="pre">default-role::</span> math</span><span>&nbsp;</span>at the top of your document, you can write<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal">`x^2`</span><span>&nbsp;</span>instead of the longer version:<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; white-space: nowrap;" class="pre">:math:`x^2`</span></span>. You can also introduce an abbreviation like this<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal">.. role:: m(math)</span>. That will allow you to write<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; white-space: nowrap;" class="pre">:m:`x^2`</span></span><span>&nbsp;</span>or<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; white-space: nowrap;" class="pre">`x^2`:m:</span></span>.</p></aside><p style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">The<span>&nbsp;</span><strong style="box-sizing: border-box;">math directive</strong><span>&nbsp;</span>is used for displayed equations. It corresponds to an<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal">equation*</span><span>&nbsp;</span>or<span>&nbsp;</span><span style="box-sizing: border-box; background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); font-family: monospace; white-space: pre-wrap;" class="docutils literal">align*</span><span>&nbsp;</span>environment in a LaTeX document. If you write:</p><pre style="box-sizing: border-box; margin-left: calc(2% + 1em); background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); padding: 0.2em; overflow-x: auto; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; div.p: Docutils supports mathematical content with a "math" directive and role. The input format is LaTeX math syntax[1] with support for literal Unicode symbols.

div.p: The math role can be used for inline mathematical expressions: :math:`\psi(r) = \exp(-2r)` will produce ψ(r)=exp⁡(−2r). Inside the backtics you can write anything you would write between dollar signs in a LaTeX document. [1]

aside.p: If you put .. default-role:: math at the top of your document, you can write `x^2` instead of the longer version: :math:. You can also introduce an abbreviation like this .. role:: m(math). That will allow you to write :m: or :m:.

div.p: A more complex example is the definition of the Fourier transform:

pre.style: box-sizing: border-box; margin-left: calc(2% + 1em); background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); padding: 0.2em; overflow-x: auto; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;

div.pre:
.. math::
:name: Fourier transform
(\mathcal{F}f)(y)
= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}^{\ n}}
\int_{\mathbb{R}^n} f(x)\,
e^{-\mathrm{i} y \cdot x} \,\mathrm{d} x.

aside.p: The supported LaTeX commands include AMS extensions (see, e.g., the Short Math Guide). Some of the shown symbols require the "amssymb" LaTeX package (or another package providing the AMS symbol macros) when exported with the "latex" writer.

The support is limited to a subset of LaTeX math by the conversion required for many output formats. For HTML, the math_output configuration setting (or the corresponding --math-output command line option) selects between alternative output formats with different subsets of supported elements. If a writer does not support math typesetting, the content is inserted verbatim.

section.p: The use of | and \| for pairs of vertical bars may produce incorrect spacing, e.g., |k|=|-k| produces |k|=|−k| and |\sin(x)| produces |sin⁡(x)|. The pairing delimiters, e.g. |−k| and |sin⁡(x)|, prevent this problem.

section.p: In LaTeX, the default font for capital Greek letters is upright/roman. Italic capital Greek letters can be obtained by loading a package providing the "ISO" math style. They are used by default in MathML.
Individual Greek italic capitals can also be achieved preceding the letter name with var like \varPhi: 𝛤𝛥𝛬𝛷𝛱𝛹𝛴𝛩𝛶𝛯𝛺

section.p: The TeX math alphabet macros are intended for mathematical variables where style variations are important semantically. They style letters and numbers with a combination of font attributes (shape, weight, family) --- non-alphanumerical symbols, function names, and mathematical text are left unchanged.
MathML uses the mathvariant style attribute or pre-styled characters from the Mathematical Alphanumeric Symbols Unicode block.

section.p: The set of characters in a given "math alphabet" varies. LaTeX may produce garbage for unsupported characters. Additional math alphabets are defined in LaTeX packages, e.g.,

li.p: \mathbfit from isomath allows vector symbols in line with the International Standard [ISO-80000-2]. E.g., \mathbfit{r}^2=x^2+y^2 becomes 𝒓2=x2+y2.
Several packages, e.g. mathrsfs, define \mathscr that selects a differently shaped "script" alphabet.

section.p: In addition to the standard accents and embellishments, other symbols can be placed above or below a base symbol with the \overset and \underset commands. The symbol is set in "scriptstyle" (smaller font size). For example, writing \overset{*}{X} becomes X* and \underset{+}{M} becomes M+.

section.p: There are also three commands that leave a space equal to the height and width of its argument. For example \phantom{XXX} results in space as wide and high as three X’s:
The commands \hphantom and \vphantom insert space with the width or height of the argument. They are not supported with math_output MathML.

section.p: There are two or three situations where the delimiter size is commonly adjusted using these commands:

The first kind of adjustment is done for cumulative operators with limits, such as summation signs. With \left and \right the delimiters usually turn out larger than necessary, and using the Big or bigg sizes instead gives better results:

pre.style: box-sizing: border-box; margin-left: calc(2% + 1em); background-color: rgb(246, 249, 248); padding: 0.2em; overflow-x: auto;
overflow-wrap: break-word; text-wrap: wrap;

section.p: The second kind of situation is clustered pairs of delimiters, where left and right make them all the same size (because that is adequate to cover the encompassed material), but what you really want is to make some of the delimiters slightly larger to make the nesting easier to see.

The third kind of situation is a slightly oversize object in running text, such as |b'd'| where the delimiters produced by \left and \right cause too much line spreading. [8] In that case \bigl and \bigr can be used to produce delimiters that are larger than the base size but still able to fit within the normal line spacing: |b'd'|.
